player.seasonOutlook: Gonzalez had one of the best seasons of his career in 2017 and kept things going early last season, owning a 2.10 ERA at the end of May. However, he posted a 6.53 ERA over his next 16 starts and the Nationals, after falling out of the playoff hunt, ultimately shipped him to the Brewers at the end of August. Gonzalez averaged just over 5.0 innings over five starts with the Brewers in September, but he allowed just six earned runs total and picked up three wins, playing a key role in the team's push to the postseason. Despite the quality month, Gonzalez played only a minor role for the team in October. He lost a few ticks off his fastball the past couple seasons and has never been great in the WHIP department, so in order to do much for fantasy players he is likely going to have to land with a team that gives him a shot at double-digit wins for the 10th straight year.

Chen hasn't met expectations since signing with Miami in January 2016, with poor health hindering his overall effectiveness. After missing most of April with an elbow issue, Chen returned to deliver a pedestrian 4.79 ERA and 7.5 K/9 across 26 starts. Chen was spectacular in the friendly confines of Marlins Park (1.62 ERA, 0.94 WHIP in 78 frames), but he paid for his fly ball-happy ways in less favorable road venues, posting a 9.27 ERA and 2.3 HR/9. Those splits are worth remembering when considering Chen in DFS or as a season-long streamer.

Lynn was a surprisingly serviceable mid-rotation arm in 2017 (3.43 ERA in 186.1 innings), but a career-low 9.7 K-BB% and .244 BABIP suggested regression was coming. Though he regained a couple ticks of velocity and raised his strikeout rate, Lynn's elevated walk rate (10.9 percent) coupled with downturns in BABIP and strand rate saddled him with a 4.77 ERA between stops with the Twins and Yankees. The Rangers were intrigued enough by Lynn's improved swing-and-miss stuff and late-season improvement to extend him a three-year contract, but Arlington isn't a great environment for any pitcher looking to rebound.

Kikuchi, a 27-year-old Japanese left-hander, signed via the major league posting system with the Seattle Mariners in January, where he'll be a regular member of their rotation in 2019. He posted a 2.51 ERA, 1.06 WHIP, 25.1 percent strikeout and 8.1 percent walk rates in 71 starts for Seibu the past three seasons combined, though a shoulder issue cost him a portion of his 2018. The Mariners will keep Kikuchi's workload in check accordingly, as he's scheduled to make roughly 30 starts, with some of them shortened in terms of pitch count. That'll cap his fantasy upside, as while he's plenty capable of a mid-threes ERA and a little shy of a strikeout per inning, he might require more maintenance than your typical starter. These days, though, the game's specialization shouldn't significantly depress Kikuchi's value, as he has a good chance at a top-60 fantasy starter year.
